Author-Name:  Matthew Gentzkow 
Author-Name:  Jesse M. Shapiro 
Title: Ideological Segregation Online and Offline 
Abstract:
 We use individual and aggregate data to ask how the Internet is changing
 the ideological segregation of the American electorate. Focusing on online
 news consumption, offline news consumption, and face-to-face social
 interactions, we define ideological segregation in each domain using
 standard indices from the literature on racial segregation. We find that
 ideological segregation of online news consumption is low in absolute
 terms, higher than the segregation of most offline news consumption, and
 significantly lower than the segregation of face-to-face interactions with
 neighbors, co-workers, or family members. We find no evidence that the
 Internet is becoming more segregated over time.  Copyright 2011, Oxford University Press.
